  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Alas, the Island
  author: Lee Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Where lies that island in the eastern sea,
    Mid vast and misty waves, a single point of blue?
    What moves me thus to weep these tears in two,
    But sorrow for Tian Heng and all his company?

    Tian Heng's spirit vast as autumn's chill domain,
    With five hundred loyal hearts who would not part—
    And he of Xianyang with the noble's mark,
    He drew down Heaven's River, washed away Qin's pain.

    Why then did Heng not turn his face to return?
    Why did his sword find only his own throat?
    Though his followers learned of his final note,
    What could they do but grieve and watch it burn?

    The lone bird now has nowhere left to rest,
    Better to follow him beneath the ground,
    Our threadbare lives—what loss if we are bound
    Together at his side, forever blessed.

    All pierced by sword on that forsaken shore,
    The mountains grieve, the capes sigh with despair,
    The setting sun casts shadows in the air.
    Alas, through countless ages evermore,

    This tangled heart—who living yet will know?
    Unless the thunder splits the very sky,
    Or rainbows stretch their crimson banners high
    To pierce the heavens with this burning woe.

    Do you not see how many shallow hearts
    Walk this earth, both old and young in time?
    Those who swore brotherhood at morning's chime
    Become sworn enemies when day departs.
  footnotes:
    - Tian Heng (田橫) was a Chinese general who resisted the Han dynasty. Rather than surrender, he and his five hundred followers chose death by suicide, making him a symbol of unwavering loyalty and righteous resistance.
    - The 'noble with the mark' (隆準) refers to Liu Bang, founder of the Han dynasty, who was said to have a prominent nose bridge. He is praised here for cleansing Qin's tyranny by drawing down the 'Heaven's River' (the will of Heaven).
    - The poem contrasts Tian Heng's steadfast loyalty with the inconstancy of ordinary people, who betray their bonds of brotherhood for personal gain.
